thread.title: Aust bonds firm ahead of RBA rate call
thread.title_full: Aust bonds firm ahead of RBA rate call | Business Spectator

author: AAP
title: Aust bonds firm ahead of RBA rate call
text:
The Australian bond market is firmer in the wake of weaker US jobs figures and ahead of the Reserve Bank's interest rate decision.
US non-farm payroll figures on Friday showed that 142,000 jobs were added to the world's largest economy in September, well below expectations of a gain of 205,000, while the unemployment rate was unchanged at 5.1 per cent.
ANZ economists said the data raised doubts about the strength of the US economy and prompted a rethink on the timing of the Federal Reserve's next move.
The market is also looking ahead at the Reserve Bank of Australia's cash rate decision.
IG markets analyst Angus Nicholson said the market expects the rate to be left unchanged but investors were nervous about the central bank's outlook on the local economy which may indicate a future rate cut.
"There is increasing pricing in the bond market that the RBA may be forced to cut rates in the near future," he said.
"This is being spurred by the slowdown in China, poor data from the US and increasing amount of data showing the Australian housing market is starting to slow down."
At 1630 AEDT on Monday, the December 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.415 (implying a yield of 2.585 per cent), up from 97.345 (2.655 per cent) on Friday.
The December 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 98.270 (1.730 per cent), up from 98.190 (1.810 per cent).
